<TEXT>
defying a government policy that promotes 
cremation rural chinese are building tombs so deluxe that some 
people are actually setting up house in them an official newspaper 
said today 
the china daily said one farmer spent 540 or about four times 
the per capita annual income in the countryside to prepare for his 
parents a final resting place fashioned out of 3000 bricks and 37 
tons of stone 
in coastal zhejiang province one farmer was found living in a 
fourroom tomb he had built for himself his wife and his late 
parents the tomb came equipped with electric lights 
the communist government has long urged chinese to abandon their 
traditional burial practices in favor of cremation burial the 
government contends is a serious drain on land resources in a 
country with 23 percent of the worlds population but only 5 percent 
of the earths arable land 
although most city people are now cremated there has been strong 
resistance to cremation in more conservative rural areas the 
defiance has increased in recent years as newly affluent villagers 
seek to honor the dead with large banquets buddhist ceremonies and 
impressive burial sites 
funeral catering services are booming while crematoria are 
closing for lack of business or dependent on government subsidies 
according to official reports 
entrepreneurs in the scenic city of hangzhou last year built 
1000 tombs almost all for overseas chinese willing to pay large 
sums to bury their remains in the motherland 
of the 6 million chinese who died in 1987 only 16 million or 
27 percent were cremated 
the englishlanguage china daily said that in the hunan county 
140 people had been injured in disputes over limited space for 
burials 
</TEXT>
