<TEXT>
an astronaut scheduled to command a shuttle 
mission this year denied a published report that he failed two tests 
for colorblindness and another astronaut called the allegation of 
colorblindness absurd 
however daniel c brandenstein chief of the astronaut corps at 
the johnson space center did not specifically deny that he is 
colorblind a condition that would have disqualified him from flying 
in space 
brandenstein who is to command a mission this year made his 
comments monday following a story in the houston chronicle the 
previous day that said he and astronaut frederick c hauck received 
waivers for medical conditions that would have otherwise grounded 
them 
hauck commanded the first postchallenger mission 
on tuesday the houston post reported that an anonymous caller to 
the newspaper said the astronaut had failed a standard 
colorblindness test in 1987 and then failed the farnsworth lantern 
test also for colorblindness 
without going into detail its not accurate brandenstein 
was quoted as saying in the article 
brandenstein said the claims about his vision are contrary to his 
performance as a navy pilot who has made 400 carrier landings 
i have a long record of operational flying in the navy with no 
problem he added 
hauck would not discuss reports he had kidney stone problems but 
he did say the allegation dan brandenstein is colorblind is 
absurd 
james c fletcher nasas chief administrator refused to comment 
on the medical records of brandenstein and hauck but he issued a 
statement from washington saying i am confident that the system 
has not been abrogated and that no one flies without qualifying by 
the book 
fletcher like other nasa officials said he would not discuss 
any individual medical records on the grounds that such records are 
legally a private matter 
the chronicle citing unidentified sources at the johnson space 
center said hauck underwent special medical treatment last year to 
dissolve kidney stones and brandenstein received a waiver earlier 
keeping him on flight status despite colorblindness 
