<TEXT>
us embassies abroad have hired hundred of 
foreign nationals for security posts and other jobs without 
background checks heightening the risk of espionage and terrorism 
a congressional report says 
the general accounting office looking at security for us posts 
in nine countries found that employees at eight of them had not 
been adequately investigated 
these shortcomings represent not only noncompliance with 
regulations but more importantly a gap in the us efforts to 
reduce the risk of espionage and terrorism at overseas posts the 
gao report said 
the gao found that of 328 local guards hired in egypt at least 
204 were not investigated by us officials it said there were no 
plans to investigate 48 guards who were hired for us posts by 
egyptian commercial contractors 
in argentina the ambassador hired a nanny and a chauffeur at his 
own expense without telling the american security officer according 
to the report later the nanny was found to have both local and us 
police records and the chauffeur was fired for helping to steal the 
ambassadors car it said 
the report did not name the ambassador 
it found that in algeria like egypt a neighbor of libya only 
52 of the 229 foreign nationals employed were investigated and none 
of the local guard force of 94 was among them 
in morocco of 821 nonamerican employees security files were 
missing on 112 and the security officer said 108 were probably never 
investigated 
in argentina 71 guards were investigated by a local contractor 
who hired them with no check by americans the us security 
officer in thailand had not investigated 183 local guards and the 
local contractor who supplied them was allowed to determine which 
ones to investigate 
a state department official said tuesday it is reviewing each 
post to see that investigations are in compliance with its rules 
but he added that the report does not seem to account for the 
various restrictions imposed by governments of the host countries 
in some countries no investigations are possible said the 
official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
</TEXT>
