<TEXT>
sales of existing homes in 1988 hit their 
highest level in nine years as purchases shifted to the lowercost 
south and midwest and consumers opted to buy less costly dwellings 
rather than leave the market a real estate trade group reported 
despite the dampening effect of rising mortgage interest rates 
sales for 1988 totaled 399 million units up 26 percent from the 
previous year and the highest since 405 million sales were recorded 
in 1979 the national association of realtors said tuesday 
we underestimated the buying power strength of the baby boom 
generation said ira gribin president of the realtors group 
the market is being driven by people who are buying in spite of 
rising rates 
the biggest sales gains were posted in the least expensive 
regions of the country 
sales in the midwest were up 61 percent during the last quarter 
of 1988 from the previous three months and sales in the south rose 
54 percent the northeast meanwhile posted a 24 percent decline 
in sales while the west recorded a 14 percent increase 
the midwest was a bright star of the nations housing sector 
last quarter and we think its improvement will continue this 
year said john a tuccillo the realtors chief economist we 
have seen activity pick up in the midwest and south and subside in 
the highcost areas of the northeast 
prices of existing homes meanwhile rose 41 percent in 1988 to 
a national median of 89100 meaning half the homes cost more and 
half cost less for the fourth quarter of 1988 the median price was 
down to 87900 
the groups survey of 62 metropolitan areas found stark 
differences in median home prices around the nation ranging from a 
high of 231200 in californias orange county which includes 
anaheim and santa ana to a low of 53500 in oklahoma city 
two other california markets san francisco and los angeles 
ranked second and fourth in cost with median resale prices of 
228100 and 191200 honolulu with a median price of 225000 
was third 
the hot markets in california and hawaii also recorded the 
nations largest price increases between the fourth quarter of 1987 
and the same period last year 
prices in orange county were up 322 percent while they rose 
296 percent in san francisco 246 percent in los angeles and 186 
percent in san diego in hawaii prices were up 164 percent 
the increased sales activity in the midwest resulted in healthy 
price appreciation in several cities in that area including 
chicago where the median price last quarter rose to 101400 up 
108 percent from the fourth quarter of 1987 
the 87200 price in minneapolisst paul was up 82 percent and 
detroits median of 73400 was up 107 percent 
in the midwest we are seeing prices increase in areas that 
were largely bypassed by the housing expansion earlier in the 
1980s tuccillo said 
while prices in the northeast remained high costs in several 
cities there showed little escalation and even dropped in some cases 
prices in fifthranked boston moved up a modest 3 percent to 
182800 
in the new york metropolitan area which includes long island and 
northern new jersey prices were down 36 percent in the last 
quarter of 1988 but still ranked sixth in the nation at 178500 
seventhranked hartford with a median home price of 165000 
saw prices edge up just 07 percent 
in the northeast prices have basically run away from family 
income tuccillo said the market is slowing down there until 
incomes can catch up 
the least expensive places to live were led by oklahoma city 
where the median price was 53500 followed by des moines iowa at 
54800 louisville ky at 55600 toledo ohio at 56400 and 
lansing mich at 56700 
prices in oklahoma city fell 101 percent from the fourth quarter 
of 1987 the sharpest drop in the survey other oildependent areas 
also recorded falling prices including houston where the median 
dropped 96 percent to 56800 and san antonio texas where the 
median fell 81 percent to 62100 
