<TEXT>
here is a chronology of key events in the 
oliver north irancontra case from his indictment through tuesdays 
developments 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
march 16 north former national security adviser john m 
poindexter and two others are indicted on charges they conspired to 
divert iranian arms sales profits to the contras i can assure you 
i will never give up we will win i just cannot tell you how 
soon north says 
march 18 north announces his retirement from the marine corps 
because he may subpoena the highest ranking officials in our 
government 
june 6 us district judge gerhard gesell who authorized 
turning over 300000 documents to the defense warns that the danger 
of exposing the nations most sensitive secrets poses a serious 
obstacle to pursuing the conspiracy charges against the four 
defendants 
june 8 gesell orders separate trials for the four defendants 
independent counsel lawrence e walsh the next day chooses north 
for the leadoff trial 
sept 30 an appeals court rebuffs an attempt by north and two 
other defendants to stop the prosecution 
nov 7 one of 16 criminal counts fabricating a document is 
dismissed 
nov 21 gesell warns that if north stands trial the court will 
have little control over the testimony of witnesses acquainted 
with high security matters he appeals to president reagan to 
decide whether north is to be pardoned 
nov 29 gesell refuses to dismiss two of the central charges 
against north conspiracy to defraud the government and theft of 
government property he dismisses a third wire fraud 
dec 1 reagan rules out a north pardon but says duty 
requires his administration to block release of secret documents 
north wants for his trial 
dec 1 mexican officials disclosed that amiram nir the israeli 
gobetween in secret us arms deals with iran died nov 30 in a 
plane crash in mexico while traveling under an assumed name 
dec 12 gesell tells north he cant use 3500 secret documents 
that he can use more than 300 roughly the same number planned to be 
introduced as evidence by the prosecution the decision removes a 
major obstacle to the trial going forward 
dec 30 north subpoenas reagan and presidentelect bush as 
defense witnesses gesell after bush is sworn in the following 
month rules that the sitting president cannot be called he 
postpones a decision regarding reagan pending further hearings 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
jan 5 prosecutors ask gesell to dismiss conspiracy and theft 
charges citing norths insistence on introducing classified 
information in his defense and the reagan administrations refusal 
to release material the judge ruled north would need gesell later 
dismisses those counts 
north remains charged with 12 crimes including lying to congress 
in 1985 and 1986 about his efforts on behalf of the contras and 
lying to the attorney general about the national security councils 
role in diverting money from the iran arms sales 
he also is accused of illegally accepting a 13800 security 
system at his home from codefendant richard secord converting to 
his own use at least 4300 in travelers checks from contra leader 
adolfo calero and conspiring to defraud the government of tax 
revenue by using a taxexempt foundation to funnel money to the 
contras 
jan 31 jury selection begins 
feb 7 lawyers for north move to stop the trial on grounds that 
the jury selection process failed to meet legal requirements gesell 
takes no immediate action 
feb 8 the justice department interrupts norths trial urging 
new safeguards to prevent him from making surprise disclosures of 
classified information gesell denies the request 
feb 9 a federal appeals court denies the justice departments 
attempt to stop norths trial on national security grounds but the 
bush administration vows to continue trying to put the proceeding on 
hold 
feb 10 the justice department seeks for a third time to delay 
norths trial contending that defense lawyers would hurt national 
security by spilling state secrets onto the public record a federal 
appeal court panel again denies the request 
feb 11 the justice department asks the supreme court to delay 
norths trial on national security grounds 
feb 12 chief justice william h rehnquist grants a delay in 
norths trial until the full supreme court can consider on feb 17 
the justice departments objections to the planned release of 
classified material by norths defense 
feb 14 gesell rejects an agreement that would have allowed the 
justice department to object at any time to defense disclosures of 
classified material gesell ruled that attorney general dick 
thornburgh may not file a series of affidavits in bits and 
pieces during norths trial 
</TEXT>
