police closed an avantgarde art exhibit today 
after a newspaper received a letter saying bombs would be placed in 
the gallery if the show continued 
it was the second time the exhibit has been closed 
police and several organizers searched the china art gallery for 
signs of a bomb as of this afternoon nothing had been found 
the beijing daily received a letter tuesday saying three bombs 
would be planted in the gallery if the show was not shut the letter 
was composed with chinese characters cut from a newspaper and pasted 
on a piece of paper organizers said 
organizers said they suspected an artist who was not picked to 
take part in the show was behind the threat 
it seems to be another kind of performance art said one 
organizer we think the artist is trying to show arts 
relationship with chinese society 
police closed the show the day it opened feb 5 when a woman 
shot her sculpture with a bb gun in defiance of a ban on performance 
art the artist and her boyfriend were detained for three days and 
then released 
other artists also defied the action art ban by tossing 
condoms and change on the floor and sitting on eggs 
the show reopened friday 
organizers said although they did not approve of the bomb threat 
they believed it could benefit modern art in china 
through this activity we will get much publicity said one 
organizer at this stage in its development chinese modern art 
needs all the publicity it can get 
the show is the largest avantgarde show in chinas history 
filling five halls of the china art gallery with more than 250 works 
many of the works are controversial some like a huge balloon 
shaped as a breast are explicitly sexual others like a portrait 
on graph paper of the late leader mao tsetung are political 
other pieces such as a dozen dead fish wrapped in plastic are 
just strange 
for decades art in china was controlled by the state and works 
that did not serve the communist party were not welcome recently 
the state has allowed more freedom in art 
