human rights campaigner andrei d sakharov said in 
a letter published wednesday he is withdrawing from the race for a 
territorial seat in a new national legislature 
sakharovs letter published in the weekly moscow news said he 
would not accept nominations from territorial districts because he 
believes he should represent the academy of sciences 
the prestigious academy where sakharov works as a nuclear 
physicist last month rejected proposals to throw his hat in the 
ring as its representative in the new 2250seat congress of 
peoples deputies the 67yearold dean of the soviet human rights 
movement was nominated to represent a moscow district but many of 
his scientific colleagues wanted him to represent them in the new 
congress 
sakharov who won the 1975 nobel peace prize said he agreed 
i feel that i am inseparably linked with the academy of which 
i have been a member 35 years sakharov wrote i have come to 
the conclusion that i should be a candidate namely of the academy in 
the new elections or not be one at all therefore i am taking the 
decision not to run anywhere except the academy of sciences of the 
ussr withdrawing my consent to run from all territorial and 
nationalterritorial districts which fielded my candidacy 
in a letter accompanying sakharovs in moscow news space 
scientist roald sagdeyev said he supports his colleagues decision 
and hopes the academy leadership will reverse its decision and 
find a way to nominate sakharov sagdeyev was also passed over 
as an academy nominee 
