<DOCNO> AP890215-0134 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the percentage of elderly americans dying in 
nursing homes rose sharply during the 1980s as hospitals began 
discharging terminally ill patients to save money a new study 
concludes 
the report largely attributed the change to medicare rules that 
encourage hospitals to release elderly patients as quickly as 
possible 
however it said that other costcutting pressures including the 
rise of health maintenance organizations may also have contributed 
dr mark a sager who directed the study said that sending 
dying people to nursing homes rather than keeping them in hospitals 
is not necessarily a bad trend 
it may be very appropriate and less costly he said in an 
interview the issue is whether nursing homes can adequately take 
care of a sicker population today than they were seeing a few years 
ago 
however sager said there is no sign that quicker hospital 
discharges have shortened these peoples lives 
medicares new payment system began in 1983 instead of covering 
patients actual expenses the program pays hospitals flat fees in 
advance for each patient hospitals get the same amount for each 
patient with a specific disease regardless of whether the patient 
stays in the hospital for a day or a month 
meanwhile another report showed medicare expenditures have risen 
less sharply than experts predicted a decade ago 
a study directed by dr louise b russell of rutgers university 
estimated the medicare payment program will be responsible for a 3 
percent reduction in the nations total health care bill which is 
expected to be 650 billion in 1990 
in 1980 the hospital insurance trust fund the branch of the 
government that actually pays medicare bills predicted it would be 
spending about 55 billion by 1990 instead it appears the actual 
expense by then will be 43 billion in 1980 dollars the study said 
the savings will amount to 18 billion in 1990 dollars 
both studies were published in thursdays new england journal of 
medicine 
sagers study found that in 1981 65 percent of all deaths among 
people over 65 occured in hospitals by 1985 this had fallen to 61 
percent at the same time the proportion of deaths occurring in 
nursing homes rose from 19 percent to 215 percent 
what has to be said is that hospitals are in a bind because 
they are being pressured by cost cutting said sager a physician 
at dean medical center in madison wis nursing homes are in a 
bind because nobody wants to pay for nursing home care patients are 
in a bind because they are in a system that does not want to provide 
continuity of care and health care financing is fragmented 
his study found that in 198384 35 states showed significant 
declines in hospital deaths while 33 reported increases in nursing 
home deaths in new york new jersey massachusetts and maryland 
states that did not initially participate in the new payment system 
there was no change in where people died 
his work also found that the changes were most pronounced in the 
midwest south and west he could not entirely explain this 
difference but said some of it might have resulted from the heavy 
concentration of hmos in these regions 
hmos try to minimize hospital stays because members pay flat 
rates for comprehensive care 
