<TEXT>
a year after the governments n reactor 
was closed backers are encouraged by a study suggesting the 
plutoniumproducing facility could find new life making a weapons 
material whose stockpiles are dwindling 
the government has been without a source of tritium a rapidly 
decaying gas used to increase the power of nuclear weapons since 
the savannah river plant in south carolina shut down last summer for 
safety reasons 
that has raised hopes in the richland area hardhit when the 
energy department closed the n reactor at its hanford weapons 
complex because of a plutonium surplus that cost 1800 jobs and 
ultimately could cost 5000 
its the newest of all the defense reactors and considerably 
newer than the savannah river reactors republican us rep sid 
morrison said tuesday this is an option and one weve worked to 
keep alive 
thenenergy secretary john herrington placed the n reactor on 
cold standby on feb 16 1988 the plant which began operating 
in 1963 had been shut down for more than a year for safety 
improvements spurred by the reactors similarity in design to the 
soviet unions chernobyl plant 
however a department of energy study released this week said the 
n reactor could be converted to make tritium within three years for 
125 million 
the nations supply of tritium is a closely guarded secret the 
energy department has proposed new tritium reactors in south 
carolina and idaho but they are a decade away from production some 
lawmakers and the pentagon have said the shortage threatens national 
security 
the bush administration now must determine future tritium needs 
and whether to restart the savannah river plants before deciding 
what to do with the n reactor said morrison whose district 
includes the sprawling facility 
restarting it would be good news for the economically ravaged 
cities of richland kennewick and pasco the closure has cost 1800 
jobs with 1000 more to be lost when shutdown work concludes by 
october according to westinghouse hanford co which operates most 
hanford operations for the energy department 
more important the closing sounded the death knell for all 5000 
plutonium production jobs at hanford by the 1990s thats when the 
stockpile of plutonium produced by the n reactor for further 
processing at hanford will run out 
the shutdown was the most disastrous thing thats ever hit this 
area said sam volpentest director for the tricity industrial 
development councils hanford division which lobbies congress for 
new projects at the 560squaremile site 
much of the economic impact of the shutdown has been delayed by 
an early retirement and voluntary layoff program and by the decision 
of many workers to seek jobs elsewhere many reactor workers filled 
other vacancies on the site 
employees are now removing the 1003 nuclear fuel rods a job 
that should be completed by the end of march 
problems began for the n reactor shortly after the 1986 chernobyl 
disaster that killed a reported 31 people and spread radiation 
around the world much was made of the n reactors design 
similarities including graphite in the reactor core and the lack of 
a containment dome 
the n reactor was shut down in january 1987 for 100 million in 
safety improvements that touched off a political battle over its 
restart 
but the issue became moot with herringtons announcement that the 
nation had ample plutonium and no longer needed the n reactor 
hanford officials all along disputed the chernobyl comparisons 
and wallace ruff manager of the defense reactor division said the 
improvements have made an already safe reactor safer the work 
included pressure tests on the containment system and improvements 
to the emergency cooling and seismic systems 
recent risk assessments on the n reactor show it to be comparable 
to commercial reactors ruff said even though energy department 
plants are not subject to nuclear regulatory commission standards 
