<TEXT>
the prosecutor in oliver norths irancontra 
case today outlined procedures which he said would would enable the 
trial to go forward with the agreement of the justice department 
under the procedures independent counsel lawrence walsh said he 
would if necessary request an affidavit from attorney general dick 
thornburgh to prevent the introduction of classified information at 
norths trial 
in a fourparagraph statement walsh said he was issuing the 
procedures in response to tuesdays order by the judge in the case 
which bars thornburgh from filing affidavits at any time during 
norths trial to block disclosure of specific classified material 
government sources speaking on condition of anonymity said the 
justice department agreed to the procedures after department 
officials met with the independent counsels staff the department 
will now go to the supreme court and seek to abandon a stay issued 
sunday at the departments request by chief justice william 
rehnquist 
walshs statement came after the judge in the case said that if 
the justice department is intent on preventing the trial it should 
do so now instead of trying to chop up the case with constant 
censorship demands 
us district judge gerhard gesell on tuesday rejected a justice 
department bid to intervene in the case whenever they feel it 
necessary to block disclosure of classified information instead 
gesell said the independent counsel prosecuting the case would have 
that authority 
norths lawyers revealed more of their planned defense on 
tuesday saying that the reagan administration offered cia covert 
support to central american nations if they would help the contras 
during a period in which congress had banned us aid 
the alleged quid pro quo added a detail to the scenario 
outlined earlier this week by norths attorneys who say reagan and 
