the air force announced wednesday it would 
conduct a fullscale environmental impact study of its plan to build 
a radio transmitter complex in an ecologically sensitive area near 
warren grove nj 
the complex dubbed the northeast regional communications 
facility is designed to guarantee international communications in 
the event of war or other national emergency supplementing the 
satellite links used now 
last november the air force informed local officials it intended 
to proceed with the project under a national security justification 
without performing an environmental impact study 
but local residents new jersey gov thomas h kean and the 
states congressional delegation all have expressed opposition or 
concern over the plan prompting the air force to reconsider the 
matter 
the air force will begin preparation of the environmental 
impact statement in the near future the service said wednesday in 
a brief statement 
there will be opportunities for public involvement in the 
process which will be announced at the appropriate times 
the air force was named to build and operate the facility by the 
defense communications agency and wants to use a 43acre site now 
owned by the federal aviation administration in warren grove in 
the heart of the pine barrens 
the pine barrens is an ecologically sensitive wilderness area 
that harbors a variety of endangered plants and wildlife it has 
been designated a national reserve since 1978 
more than a dozen radio towers would be constructed at the faa 
site which is located about 20 miles southeast of mcguire air force 
