<TEXT>
here is a chronology of some of the main events in the war in 
afghanistan 
 
1978 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
april the prosoviet marxist party of afghanistan overthrows 
the afghan republic and installs nur mohammad taraki as president 
armed noncommunist resistance begins 
 
1979 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
march 12 the national liberation front a moslem group calls 
for jihad or holy war against kabul government 
july soviets deploy first combat unit in afghanistan a 400man 
airborne battalion 
september taraki killed in intraparty showdown with deputy 
hafizullah amin 
december massive soviet airlift of 5000 troops to afghanistan 
soviet commandos attack presidential palace amin is killed and 
babrak karmal becomes president 
 
1980 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
january united nations demands immediate unconditional and 
total withdrawal of foreign troops from afghanistan 
february soviet troop strength increases to 75000 and 
eventually to 115000 by western estimates 
 
1982 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june in geneva un official diego cordovez conducts first 
indirect peace talks between afghanistan and pakistan which speaks 
for afghan resistance 
 
1984 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
april soviets conduct saturation bombing of guerrilla 
strongholds and villages 
august pakistan protests to kabul government about repeated 
aerial bombing and crossborder shelling 
 
1985 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
may in pakistan fundamentalist moslem guerrillas join 
moderates to form a sevenparty coalition 
december afghanistan offers timetable for soviet withdrawal 
 
1986 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
may karmal replaced by najib former head of secret police 
july soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev announces plans to 
withdraw six regiments from afghanistan washington later says 
forces mainly were unnecessary antiaircraft units and were replaced 
by armored regiments 
september guerrillas supported by significant us arms 
shipments reportedly receive first us stinger antiaircraft 
missiles within months they reportedly shoot down average of one 
enemy aircraft per day 
 
1987 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
january najib declares unilateral ceasefire it is ignored by 
both sides and guerrillas reject powersharing with communists 
october surveys estimate that more than 12 million afghans 
have died in war and that 29 million afghans have fled to pakistan 
and 23 million to iran december one of gorbachevs chief 
advisers tells reporters he expects soviet union to pull out of 
afghanistan in 1988 
 
1988 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
january pakistan says it will accept some communist involvement 
in future afghan government as price for soviet withdrawal 
february gorbachev offers to withdraw soviet troops beginning 
may 15 and ending 10 months later if an accord is signed by march 
15 cordovez announces near agreement on soviet pullout and new 
round of talks in geneva 
march agreement reached that soviet troop withdrawal must be 
completed within nine months of starting date negotations continue 
past gorbachevs march 15 target date 
april 14 the soviet union pakistan the united states and the 
afghan government sign unbrokered accord in geneva arranging for 
the withdrawal of 115000 red army troops from afghanistan 
may 15 soviets pull out from eastern afghanistan as rebels 
continue attacks on soviet troops moscow accuses foreign sponsors 
of stepping up weapons shipments to guerrillas 
aug 15 the second phase of the troop withdrawal begins more 
than half of the soviet troops in the country have been evacuated 
since pullout began 
nov 4 the soviet union citing continued military aid to the 
guerrillas from pakistan and the united states says it is 
indefinitely suspending the pullout 
 
1989 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
jan 23 soviet and afghan troops shell both ends of a major 
tunnel on the salang highway the main route for soviet troops 
leaving kabul western diplomats say hundreds of civilians are 
killed in several villages in the region 
jan 24 western diplomats say the soviet withdrawal is in full 
swing even though moscow has not said whether it has resumed 
pullout 
feb 7 a soviet foreign ministry official says 15000 soviet 
soldiers were killed during the war including 2000 who died during 
the withdrawal 
feb 10 afghan rebel leaders based in pakistan and iran meet to 
discuss forming a postwar government but the talks break off over 
disputes on power sharing and including disparate factions in new 
government 
feb 15 the red army commander for afghanistan leads the last 
contingent of his troops across a border bridge ending the 
nineyear intervention the united nations confirms the soviet 
occupation is over 
