<TEXT>
the 81yearold woman sat quietly in a waiting 
room her priestly robes gathered about her as she remembered the 
perilous journey across wartorn china that culminated with her 
ordination in 1944 as the first female priest in the anglican 
communion 
the issue was one of pastoral necessity no male priest dare 
run the risk of being stationed in macao a tiny portuguese 
territory on the southern chinese coast 
but the break with 2000 years of christian tradition 
reverberated thousands of miles away in england and in 1946 the 
rev florence timoi li was given an ultimatum she must resign or 
the bishop who ordained her would be forced to resign 
theres no problem the chinese woman recently recalled 
thinking then i would give up my title i dont only want the 
title 
last week more than four decades after she acceded to church 
pressure to preseve an allmale priesthood li helped elevate the 
rev barbara c harris into the highest echelons of the anglican 
hierarchy 
in my life i can see the first woman bishop li said it 
made me hopeful things are realized now 
harris triumph refocused attention on the historical role of li 
who quietly continued her religious work in china after world war ii 
and through the cultural revolution while the battle for female 
anglican priests raged in the united states and elsewhere 
the episcopal church approved female priests in 1976 two years 
after 11 women were illegally ordained in a service in 
philadelphia 
one of the 11 the rev i carter heyward said it was an 
extraordinarily profound and moving experience to be a 
concelebrant with li at the consecration service 
i feel part of a great chain said the rev suzanne r hiatt 
another member of the philadelphia 11 
while advocates for the ordination of women have often taken 
matters into their own hands with lobbying and illegal 
ordinations lis path to the priesthood was different 
in much beloved daughter his book about li ted harrison 
said she had been working as a priest in all but name in macao 
during world war ii when bishop ro hall made his decision to 
ordain her nearby hong kong had fallen to the japanese and travel 
to macao had become dangerous as people sought to flee there 
with male priests denied permission to go to macao li was 
authorized to baptize marry bury and eventually even distribute 
holy communion 
in a letter to the archbishop of canterbury explaining his 
decision to ordain li bishop hall said please be sure that my 
reason was not theoretical views of the equality of men and women 
but the needs of my people for the sacraments and the manifest gift 
of the pastoral charisma 
as news of her ordination spread to england protests mounted 
against halls unilateral decision to break with church tradition 
in an interview at harris consecration li recalled her reaction 
when she realized the uproar threatened hall who had refused even 
before the archbishop of canterbury to back down 
i pray quietly she said 
she said it took her a brief time to decide to stop functioning 
as a priest because she knew the act of ordination placed a calling 
upon her that could not be revoked even if she no longer held the 
title publicly 
this holy order i never put it off i work for the church 
quietly calmly for the rest of my life she said 
the ordination of li who works as a priest now in toronto was 
eventually recognized she celebrated holy communion according to 
the chinese anglican rite as early as christmas eve 1957 but there 
are still reminders that women clergy are not universally accepted 
in the anglican communion 
thus archbishop of canterbury robert runcie warmly welcomed li 
to westminster abbey in 1984 for a service marking the 40th 
anniversary of her ordination but li and the other women clergy 
could not officiate at communion because the church of england still 
does not accept women clergy the church of england and the 
episcopal church are among 27 selfgoverning churches in the 70 
millionmember anglican communion 
reflecting on her own experience li said she has no doubt god 
called harris to be the female bishop in the anglican communion 
he opens a proper way for women to help their church to move 
on to give more help to people especially the female good news 
to the female li said god uses all of his creatures he would 
like every one of us to create a beautiful world 
