<DOCNO> AP890215-0221 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
dual trading is a misunderstood and essential 
element of the commodity futures markets and its potential for 
abuse can be offset by closer surveillance say top officials of the 
chicago board of trade 
dual trading the practice among floor brokers of trading both 
for their own accounts and those of brokeragefirm customers has 
long been cited by critics as a potential source of fraud 
the debate has heated up since the revelation jan 19 of a broad 
federal investigation of suspected trading fraud at the chicago 
board of trade and the chicago mercantile exchange 
but board of trade chairman karsten mahlmann and president thomas 
donovan said tuesday that dual trading helps ensure active liquid 
markets by providing an incentive for floor brokers to stay in the 
pits and trade when the flow of orders from the public runs slow 
federal rules require brokers to execute all their pending 
customer orders before trading for their own accounts thus giving 
customers the first crack at profiting from price fluctuations 
mahlmann said the exchanges board of directors voted to 
tentatively retain dual trading a decision announced last week 
because through the expansion of the surveillance system we could 
eliminate any and all potential abuses of dual trading and keep the 
benefit 
the rival chicago mercantile exchange is still considering making 
changes in its trading rules including dual trading 
theres nothing wrong with dual trading per se donovan said 
the problem is when someone would trade ahead of a customer and 
we can detect that abuse 
the board of trade hopes to better detect such abuses through a 
1 million upgrade this year of its computerized trade 
reconstruction system an electronic system that officials estimate 
can now catch about 90 percent of all improper trades the goal is 
100 percent 
on another matter mahlmann said he was not involved in the 
hiring by his own brokerage firm of two salesmen who have since been 
indicted on fraud charges 
the two salesmen michael n kolb and jan y biesiadecki were 
indicted by a federal grand jury jan 17 on charges they defrauded 
investors while working for first commodity corp of boston a 
futures brokerage firm that collapsed in 1986 after its expulsion 
from the midamerica commodity exchange a board of trade affiliate 
sixteen other former first commodity employees also were indicted 
mahlmann is the chairman of stotler amp co a large chicagobased 
commodity futures brokerage that hired kolb and biesiadecki last 
year according to records of the national futures association a 
selfregulatory arm of the futures industry 
kolb hired in march 1988 still works for stotler biesiadecki 
hired in november 1988 left stotler on jan 24 and is currently not 
registered with the national futures association 
the hirings of former first commodity salesmen by stotler and by 
rbamph inc a brokerage firm headed by a highranking executive of 
the chicago mercantile exchange have raised questions about the 
industrys ability to police itself 
mahlmann said board of trade activities had consumed almost 100 
percent of his time over the past two years and that he had not 
been involved with individual hirings at stotler during that time 
he also said all salespeople hired by stotler had been registered 
with the national futures association which is funded by the 
nations 11 futures exchanges through a pertrade fee on public 
transactions and carries a federal mandate to screen and register 
all commodities salespeople 
as a brokerage firm there is a reliance that goes with the 
registration he said 
but robert wilmouth president and chief executive officer of the 
chicagobased association said hiring decisions ultimately are made 
by brokerage firms 
rbamph is headed by john f sandner the immediate past chairman of 
the chicago merc who now holds the title of senior policy adviser 
at the exchange 
rbamph employed at least three former first commodity salesmen last 
year all of whom left the firm before they were indicted 
sandner has said he was not directly involved in the hirings and 
that his firm has not had any customer complaints relating to their 
activities 
</TEXT>
