<TEXT>
union carbide corps 470 million 
settlement with the indian government over the 1984 bhopal gas leak 
pleased wall street but was criticized by a prominent attorney who 
originally was involved in the case 
they got off criminally cheap said melvin belli the 
attorney who represented the interests of about 2000 plaintiffs 
before the cases were transferred from us courts to india 
we had that amount of money two years ago in new york and it 
wasnt enough and it isnt enough belli said tuesday in a 
telephone interview from san francisco he added that he thought two 
or three times the 470 million would have been fairer 
the stock market however was delighted by the settlement which 
was ordered by the supreme court of india sitting in new delhi 
union carbides stock price soared 212 to 3125 a share in 
new york stock exchange trading after news of the settlement and the 
companys estimate that it expected a relatively mild impact on its 
earnings from the agreement 
the indian court ordered the danburybased chemical company to 
make payment by march 31 thereby settling all claims resulting from 
the leak of deadly methyl isocyanate at the bhopal pesticide plant 
which was operated by union carbides indian subsidiary 
more than 3300 people died as a result of the dec 2 1984 
leak the worlds worst industrial disaster the plant has been 
closed since the accident 
the indian government sued union carbide for 3 billion in 
damages claiming company negligence caused the leak union carbide 
maintains that sabotage by a disgruntled employee was to blame 
