automakers suffered a 15 percent drop in sales of 
domesticmade cars and light trucks in early february over a year 
ago reflecting rising interest rates and declining incentives 
the companies reported tuesday that during the feb 110 period 
they sold vehicles at an average daily rate of 27770 compared with 
a rate of 32749 during the same time in 1988 
car sales were off 18 percent led by chrysler corps drop of 
nearly 31 percent and light truck sales fell by 10 percent 
the decline occurred partly because there were more enticing 
incentives being offered in the market during early february last 
year incentives are available now but only on a smaller number of 
cars than in early february a year ago 
interest rates also have crept up since early february last year 
i think the recent rise in interest rates have hurt sales a 
little bit said analyst scott merlis of morgan stanley amp co of 
new york also they finished 88 on a very strong note 
so far this year car and light truck sales are off 44 percent 
