<TEXT>
a lot of english wine should never have been made 
admits the head of the english vineyards association 
or if its made it shouldnt be drunk and certainly not sold 
for money says retired british navy commander geoffrey bond 
but having said that there is far far less proportionately 
bad english wine than almost anybody elses 
english wine 
yes this land of lager lovers and sherry sippers has a 
burgeoning domestic wine industry 
even fans admit it will never never push the great european 
vintages off the shelves mainly because few grape varieties can 
survive thrive and ripen in the cold wet climate 
but englands 360 vineyards did produce 108500 gallons of wine 
in 1987 and the industry gets about 10 percent bigger every year 
bond said 
most english wines are white and more sweet than dry theyre 
best as aperitifs or accompaniments to white meat fruit and salads 
there is a very clean and distinct crispness a fresh crispness 
about english wine which follows a very flowery bouquet bond 
said there is perhaps a tendency to sharpness and acidity which 
rather than condemning it identifies it 
wine writer kathryn mcwhirter says tactfully i think theyre 
quite interesting as a sort of rare occasion drink because theyre 
english and its interesting to drink wines from different places 
most have good fruit flavor she said but they tend to be 
rather thin 
english vineyards are concentrated among the farms and fruit 
orchards of the southeast but grapes grow as far west as truro in 
cornwall and one even claims to be the worlds most northerly 
commercial vineyard 
the romans planted the first english grapes about 2000 years 
ago and the domesday book records nearly 50 vineyards in southern 
england in 1086 
king henry viii wiped out the industry when he closed the last 
roman catholic monastery in 1526 at a time when the map of the 
monasteries mirrored the map of the vineyards 
a renaissance began after world war ii when scientistcumamateur 
gardener ray barrington brock set out as a hobby to discover which 
grapes would grow best in southern england 
for years winemaking remained a hobby and tax writeoff and most 
vintners need another source of income to survive 
david westphal of penshurst vineyards in kent relies on tourism 
and his apple orchard and in honor of his fathers australian 
roots raises rare sheep and small kangaroos called wallabies a 
wallaby is hidden in every label on his wine bottles 
westphal says one of his biggest problems is getting the english 
to try english wine the english are very conservative they dont 
like to try quite often you get the response ooohhh thats 
nice you know as if you were going to give them arsenic 
only 1350 acres of land is devoted to english vineyards which 
bond admits is infinitesimally small compared with germany or 
california 
at full production and with better weather output could 
increase tenfold bond said recent summers have been particularly 
wet and gales ruined much of the 1987 crop 
english winegrowers favor hardy german grapes particularly 
mueller thurgau a cross between the riesling and sylvaner vines 
its germanys most widely grown grape and accounts for 30 percent 
of all grapes planted in england bond said 
there just isnt enough sun to ripen red grapes for a fullbodied 
wine he said although a handful of brave souls continue to 
experiment 
most english wine is sold directly from the winery or to local 
hotels and restaurants very little is exported and its difficult 
to find in london stores 
however carr taylor vineyards near hastings in the southeast 
sells its sparkling wine to french hotels and eateries including 
the secondstage restaurant at the eiffel tower and supplies its 
1987 schonburger a still white wine on some british airways routes 
to canada 
elmham park winery in norfolk more than 100 miles northeast of 
london claims to be the worlds most northerly commercial vineyard 
and said it recently sold 200 cases of its blended 1986 dry white 
wine to a parisian wine merchant 
many english wines not to be confused with british wines which 
are made from imported concentrates are available in the 7 range 
to the consternation of winemakers as much as 175 of the 
bottle price is is excise tax four times the average of the 
12nation european economic community to which britain belongs 
</TEXT>
