<TEXT>
morgan stanley amp co said wednesday it has 
abandoned a voluntary restraint on a controversial form of 
computerized stock trading that was widely blamed for price 
volatility during and after the october 1987 crash 
the move by the venerable investment banking firm ended a 
ninemonth suspension on socalled index arbitrage program trading 
by morgan stanley for its own account 
morgan was one of several brokerages that restricted use of the 
technique for their own accounts in may because of a public outcry 
that index arbitrage program trading was injecting wild price swings 
into the stock market without regard to underlying values the firms 
continued to use it for customers 
bear stearns amp co another prominent indexarbitrage program 
trader that had limited use of the technique for its own account 
resumed it this past summer 
index arbitrage program trading refers to the use of big 
computers to instantly sell massive amounts of stock in new york and 
simultaneously buy the underlying stockindex futures in chicago or 
vice versa to profit from temporary price disparities between the 
two markets 
some studies of the oct 19 1987 the worst stock panic in 
history said index arbitrage program trading may have played a role 
in aggravating the crisis and contributing to the record 508point 
drop in the dow jones industrial average that day 
the joint industry solutions and the significant reduction in 
market volatility since oct 19 1987 have permitted an increase in 
confidence in the us equity market morgan said in a statement 
about its decision to resume index arbitrage program trading 
morgan also said it believes index arbitrage plays an important 
economic role in linking the futures and underlying stock markets 
last february the new york stock exchange banned the use of its 
computers for index arbitrage program trading on days when the dow 
average rose or fell 50 points from the previous days close 
that limitation dubbed the collar was scrapped last oct 
19 on the crash anniversary replaced by a broader set of reforms 
that included temporary trading halts if the dow average fell 250 
points or more in a day 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

